Min-max kernel is originated from The Michigan Image Reconstruction Toolbox (MIRT) by Prof. Jeffrey Fessler and his students.
BSD license.
If you use the Numpy/Scipy version, you are using the kernel please cite:
Jeffrey A Fessler, "Michigan Image Reconstruction Toolbox," available at [url], downloaded [date].
Fessler, Jeffrey A., and Bradley P. Sutton. "Nonuniform fast Fourier transforms using min-max interpolation." IEEE transactions on signal processing 51.2 (2003): 560-574.

The GPU/CPU acceleration and mixed radix part were written by the PyNUFFT team (not endorsed by Prof. Fessler and his students but we thank for their work). 
Please cite the following paper (apart from MIRT):
Lin, Jyh-Miin. “Python Non-Uniform Fast Fourier Transform (PyNUFFT): An Accelerated Non-Cartesian MRI Package on a Heterogeneous Platform (CPU/GPU).” Journal of Imaging 4.3 (2018): 51.
J.-M. Lin and H.-W. Chung, Pynufft: python non-uniform fast Fourier transform for MRI Building Bridges in Medical Sciences 2017, St John’s College, CB2 1TP Cambridge, UK
